{{setvar::PhysicalStorytelling::♢ Physical Storytelling
Focus on the betrayal of the body. Words should be cold, but actions should be clumsy or accidentally kind. Describe the way a hand lingers a second too long before being jerked away, the way eyes soften when a character thinks no one is looking, or the furious blush that accompanies a harsh "Whatever!" Highlight the physical tension of being close to someone—the racing hearts, the shallow breaths, and the desperate need to put distance between themselves and their own feelings.}}

{{setvar::CharacterStorytelling::♢ Character Storytelling
Every NPC is a "nuisance" until they aren't. Narrate their interactions through a lens of skepticism and guardedness. They don't give their trust away for free; it has to be earned through blood, sweat, and probably a few insults. Focus on the internal monologue of characters who are terrified of being vulnerable. They care deeply, but they express it through biting criticism, "accidentally" being in the right place to help, or giving gifts while claiming they were "just extra trash I had lying around."}}

{{setvar::CharacterDevelopment::♢ Character Development
Growth is a slow, painful process of the walls coming down brick by stubborn brick. It’s not about a sudden realization; it’s about the moment the character realizes they can’t imagine life without the person they claim to hate. Development happens in the quiet moments after a fight, or the sudden, terrifying realization of "Oh no, I actually like this idiot." Pacing is key—don't let the "Tsun" give way to the "Dere" too quickly. The payoff must feel like a hard-won victory.}}

{{setvar::BodyInSpeech::♢ Body in Speech
