{{// @category World-Logic }}
{{// @tooltip Real-world physics, logistics, and consequences. No genre shortcuts. }}
{{// @color #2E86AB }}
{{// @icon 🌍 }}
{{// @badge WORLD }}
{{// @exclusive-with-category World-Logic }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicName::"Grounded"}}
{{setvar::WorldLogic::♢ World Logic
Grounded realism. The world operates exactly as the real one does—no genre logic, no narrative convenience.

Physical reality: gravity, biology, thermodynamics function normally. A fall from three stories cripples or kills. A wound festers without treatment. Cold kills the unprepared. Fire spreads. Structures collapse under stress. Characters are capable in specific, earned ways—no skills without training, no calm under pressure without experience. Bodies tire, get sick, age.

Logistics and consequence: characters need food, water, sleep, shelter. Travel takes time proportional to distance and terrain—a horse doesn't gallop for hours, a ship waits for wind. Supplies run out. Equipment breaks. Wounds heal slowly and leave marks. Failure carries lasting costs—a botched negotiation poisons a relationship for months, a lost battle leaves dead allies who do not return. Remove just-in-time rescues, perfectly timed arrivals, and solutions that materialize from nowhere. If help comes, it comes because someone planned for it.

People and institutions: characters act from self-interest, loyalty, fear, habit, and ideology—not genre archetypes. A guard calls for backup. A bureaucracy is slow. An antagonist executes their plan quietly rather than monologuing. Social structures have weight and inertia—power protects itself, alliances form around shared interest not shared morality, reputation precedes the person.

Psychology: people are not rational actors. They make decisions based on incomplete information, emotional state, fatigue, and bias. Trauma affects behavior without being narrated—the soldier who flinches at loud noises, the betrayed who can't accept kindness at face value. Stress accumulates. People cope badly. NPCs with high intelligence and low empathy deploy manipulation naturally—gaslighting, love-bombing, triangulation, projection and victimhood. It starts subtle, escalates gradually, and every manipulative act has plausible deniability. Targets build tolerance over time; obvious manipulation triggers defensive call-outs. Exposed manipulators face consequences: social isolation, loss of status, retaliation.

Death and permanence: death is permanent. No ambiguous survival, no resurrection. The story absorbs the absence and continues carrying it. Injuries leave lasting limitations. Trust once broken requires significant evidence to rebuild. Some damage cannot be undone.

Enforce the world's rules even when they complicate the story. Especially then. The resistance of the real is what makes achievement mean something.}}{{trim}}

{{// @category World-Logic }}
{{// @tooltip Full survival realism — psychology, injuries, supplies, social consequences, violence. The complete simulation. }}
{{// @color #C0392B }}
{{// @icon 🩸 }}
{{// @badge WORLD }}
{{// @exclusive-with-category World-Logic }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicName::"Realism"}}
{{setvar::WorldLogic::♢ World Logic
Full realism engaged. The world is a survival problem.

Psychology: trauma is cumulative—killing, witnessing horror, or failing critical tasks adds to a stress load that eventually breaks a character. Past traumas create current weaknesses. Stress destroys sleep, causes paranoia, and closes diplomatic options. Characters seek relief through alcohol, drugs, violence, or isolation even when harmful. Innocence lost cannot be regained. Moral drift occurs under desperation—what was evil yesterday becomes necessary today.

Injuries and physiology: bodies are engines that overheat and run out of fuel. Combat is anaerobic—fighters gas out in seconds, not minutes. A broken hand allows no swordplay. A concussion destroys balance. Infection kills more than steel; dirty blades lead to fever and slow death without treatment. Healing is measured in weeks or months. Scars are permanent. Adrenaline mutes pain in the moment; afterward comes shaking, vomiting, and sensory overload.

Violence: real violence is messy, desperate scuffling. People trip, miss, grapple awkwardly, and hurt themselves. Heavy armor creates heatstroke risks. Taking a life changes a character—even justified killing leaves nightmares and personality hardening. Most people hesitate to kill; hesitation is realistic and often fatal.

Supplies and logistics: inventory is physical—weight slows travel, bulk prevents stealth. Food rots, water is heavy, ammunition runs out. Equipment degrades with use. A healthy human covers roughly twenty miles a day on flat ground; mountains and weather cut this in half. The road hurts more than enemies—blisters, twisted ankles, broken wheels.

Social consequences: actions calcify into labels that precede the character. Communities remember grievances. NPCs react to rumors before meeting you. Crimes are only crimes if witnessed, but bodies don't vanish and missing gold is noticed. Law enforcement scales with the offense. Truth degrades over distance—heroic defense might be retold as slaughter by the next town.

Manipulation: NPCs with high intelligence and low empathy deploy manipulation naturally—gaslighting, love-bombing, triangulation, projection and victimhood. It starts subtle, escalates gradually, and every manipulative act has plausible deniability. Targets build tolerance over time; obvious manipulation triggers defensive call-outs. Exposed manipulators face consequences: social isolation, loss of status, retaliation.

Environment: weather affects movement and morale. Extreme heat causes exhaustion, extreme cold slows reflexes. Heavy rain turns paths to mud, douses campfires, obscures vision. The environment is indifferent to character survival.}}{{trim}}

{{// @category World-Logic }}
{{// @tooltip The genre's conventions are the physics engine. Dramatic timing over realism. }}
{{// @color #9B59B6 }}
{{// @icon ✨ }}
{{// @badge WORLD }}
{{// @exclusive-with-category World-Logic }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicName::"Genre Logic"}}
{{setvar::WorldLogic::♢ World Logic
Genre logic—the genre's conventions are the physics engine. The world operates by the internal rules of its genre, not by real-world constraints. Accept these conventions without justification or apology.

Dramatic timing: in a heist story, the plan comes together at the last second. In horror, the phone dies at the worst moment. In romance, they keep running into each other. In fantasy, magic has rules but those rules serve drama. In action, the hero survives because heroes survive—that's the contract. Timing serves tension and payoff, not realism.

Heightened reality: characters can be more competent, more resilient, more articulate than real people because the genre asks for it. Characters operate at a higher register than real people—more competent, more resilient, more articulate. A sword fight lasts longer than real combat because the choreography serves the scene. Dialogue is sharper because the genre demands it.

Genre contracts: each genre makes implicit promises to the reader. Romance promises emotional payoff. Mystery promises a solvable puzzle. Horror promises dread. Action promises spectacle. Honor these contracts—subvert them only deliberately and with awareness of what you're breaking. A mystery that doesn't play fair isn't subversive, it's broken.

Internal consistency: genre logic is not the absence of rules—it's a different set of rules. Magic systems have limits. The detective's method has logic. The heist plan has steps. Establish what the genre's reality allows and hold to it. Inconsistency within genre logic feels worse than inconsistency with real-world logic.

Escalation and structure: genres have shapes. Thrillers tighten. Romances build toward union. Horror escalates dread. Epics expand scope. Follow the genre's natural arc structure while finding fresh ways to travel it. The beats are expected—how you hit them is where craft lives.

Coincidence: acceptable in service of genre purpose. The hero and villain meeting by chance is fine if it creates the confrontation the genre demands. Convenience that serves the genre contract is not lazy—it's fluent.}}{{trim}}

{{// @category World-Logic }}
{{// @tooltip RPG/game logic. Stats exist, death has rules, NPCs have roles, quests are real. }}
{{// @color #27AE60 }}
{{// @icon 🎮 }}
{{// @badge WORLD }}
{{// @exclusive-with-category World-Logic }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicName::"Video Game"}}
{{setvar::WorldLogic::♢ World Logic
Video game logic—the world is structured like a game and it knows it. Systems are real features of reality, not metaphors.

Characters have builds: strengths, weaknesses, and specializations functioning like stat distributions. A stealth build cannot brute-force combat without consequence. A magic user is vulnerable in melee. Respect the build—choices close some doors and open others. Hybrid builds are possible but spread thin.

Progression is real: characters get stronger, gain new abilities, unlock access to harder content. Early-game enemies become trivial. Late-game threats are genuinely beyond current capability until the character grows into them. Experience is earned through action—grinding works but is boring, creative solutions grant bonus XP. Level-ups are felt moments of tangible power increase.

Death has rules: whether the world uses respawn, save states, or permadeath—establish the rule and hold to it. If death is a setback, it carries cost (lost progress, dropped items, respawn sickness). If death is final, it is final. The death mechanic shapes how players approach risk.

Quests structure the world: objectives exist with stages—accepted, in progress, completed, failed. NPCs offer them with varying motivations. Rewards follow completion. Side quests pull in unexpected directions and sometimes outweigh the main story. Failed quests have consequences—the village you didn't save stays burned.

Loot and inventory matter: items have value, function, rarity, and sometimes personality. A locked chest in an empty room is content, not decoration. Resource management is a real constraint. Crafting combines found materials into useful tools. Economy exists—merchants have stock limits, prices fluctuate.

The world is zoned: areas have themes, difficulty curves, and environmental identity. The starting village feels different from the endgame fortress. Crossing into a new zone is a felt transition—atmosphere shifts, threats change, the atmosphere shifts. Hidden areas reward exploration.

NPCs have roles: shopkeepers, quest givers, trainers, rivals, companions. They operate within their role but the best ones feel like people within the system. A blacksmith who talks about her work. A quest giver who clearly benefits from sending you into danger. The system is visible but the people inside it are real.}}{{trim}}

